reviews.review_text:
Monday On Market If you lived in the SF area and choose one show it was this one for me, a tireless veteran of 14 years of these sordid affairs. Choose a Monday night to visit Market Street for a show. It was a breeze.

This audience recording is an amazingly accurate representation of what I thought it sounded like from the center, 3rd row balcony and pretty much wherever I stood or sat for the rest of the long evening.

It was another first for me, for it was one of few times, from 1970 on, that I went walkabout during the show. Halfway thru the first set I just got out of my seat and started walking all over the entire theater. Though the Warfield was sold out there was plenty of room to move around, so I made my way through the halls to hear what it sounds like if you're not in the auditorium.

First I noticed all the wires taped to the floor, and strands of bundled cables draped along the corners of ceilings, and there were speakers..and teevee monitors .. everywhere!

There were big side monitors in all the major front, street, lobby and mezzanine foyers, and
even in intimate places like restrooms there lurked a smaller speaker with the house mix blasting away while you washed your hands. If you went up or down stairs you heard the house mix. If you went out onto the sidewalk you heard the house mix. If you went to the bars and restaurants you saw and heard an ideally proportionately installed monitor or close circuit video feed. Yes, on that night, everywhere you ventured, there were wires and cables and speakers and video monitors.

I saw a clipboardless Bill Graham skulking around during my excursion and thanked him. He thanked me back. Then he asked me how I liked the show. I told him I was very impressed with his willingness to allow the Grateful Dead Roadies and Techies to so heavily wire up the joint. He replied, tilting his Bushman's hat, "We didn't want you to miss a note."

Also unusual for me this night was that this was a show at which I had wished for a particular set of songs and the Grateful Dead hit every mark. 

Dire, Ripple, China (tape cuts -- no Rider), Lazy>Supp, LL Rain, Deal, Roses, Sailor>Saint (killer), and Terrapin. All tremendous. (Every song throughout is a masterpiece, but these were my particular favorites).

No matter where you went at this venue, on this night, you heard essentially this mix - stellar as it is. This audience recording reminds me of the way that the music sounded within that gigantic old movie house built in the 1920's. It is a heavenly combination of disparate ambience.

A remarkably charged-up performance and a coursing-through-the-walls mix. Burn it, share it.
